BeanFactory is the core interface for accessing Spring beans. Bean lifecycle knowledge prevents production bugs.

BEANFACTORY vs APPLICATIONCONTEXT:
```
BeanFactory (Low-level)
- Lazy initialization
- Lower memory
- Used internally

ApplicationContext (High-level)
- Eager initialization
- AOP support
- Used in production
```

BEAN LIFECYCLE:
```
1. INSTANTIATION
2. PROPERTY INJECTION
3. AWARE INTERFACES
   - BeanNameAware.setBeanName()
   - BeanFactoryAware.setBeanFactory()
   - ApplicationContextAware.setApplicationContext()
4. @PostConstruct
5. InitializingBean.afterPropertiesSet()
6. POST-PROCESSING
7. USAGE
8. @PreDestroy
9. DisposableBean.destroy()
10. DESTROYED
```

CODE:
```java
@Component
public class DataSource implements BeanNameAware,
    InitializingBean, DisposableBean {

    @Override
    public void setBeanName(String name) {
        System.out.println("BeanName set: " + name);
    }

    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        System.out.println("@PostConstruct");
    }

    @Override
    public void afterPropertiesSet() throws Exception {
        System.out.println("afterPropertiesSet");
    }

    @PreDestroy
    public void cleanup() {
        System.out.println("@PreDestroy");
    }
}
```

COMMON PITFALLS:
1. Accessing uninitialized dependencies in constructor
2. Heavy initialization in @PostConstruct (blocks startup)
3. Forgetting @PreDestroy for cleanup
4. Circular dependencies

BEST PRACTICES:
```java
// Light constructor
public Service() { }

// Heavy initialization in @PostConstruct
@PostConstruct
public void init() {
    resource = loadExpensiveResource();
}

// Clean up in @PreDestroy
@PreDestroy
public void cleanup() {
    resource.close();
}
```

When multiple beans of same type exist, @Qualifier resolves ambiguity. Essential for complex applications.

THE PROBLEM:
```java
interface PaymentService { }

@Component
class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentService { }

@Component
class PayPalPayment implements PaymentService { }

// ERROR: Multiple beans match!
@Autowired
private PaymentService payment;
```

SOLUTION:
```java
@Autowired
@Qualifier("creditCardPayment")
private PaymentService payment;
```

CUSTOM QUALIFIER:
More type-safe approach.

```java
@Target({ElementType.FIELD, ElementType.PARAMETER})
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
@Qualifier
public @interface PaymentMethod {
    String value();
}

@Component
@PaymentMethod("creditcard")
class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentService { }

@Autowired
@PaymentMethod("creditcard")
private PaymentService payment;
```

PRIMARY BEAN:
```java
@Component
@Primary  // Use as default
class CreditCardPayment implements PaymentService { }

@Autowired
private PaymentService payment;  // Gets CreditCardPayment
```

OBJECTPROVIDER (Modern):
```java
@Autowired
private ObjectProvider<PaymentService> paymentProvider;

public void checkout() {
    PaymentService payment = paymentProvider.getIfAvailable();
}
```

BEST PRACTICES:
1. Use custom @Qualifier annotations (type-safe)
2. Mark one bean as @Primary
3. Avoid string literals (use constants)
4. Document why multiple implementations exist
5. Consider factory pattern

PRODUCTION: Missing @Qualifier causes NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException on startup.

Bean scope controls lifecycle and visibility. Wrong choice causes critical production bugs.

SINGLETON (Default):
```
One instance, shared across entire application
- Created at startup
- Reused for every injection
- Thread-safe if stateless
- Memory efficient

UserService s1 = context.getBean(UserService.class);
UserService s2 = context.getBean(UserService.class);
s1 == s2  // true
```

PROTOTYPE:
```
New instance for every injection
- Created on demand
- Spring doesn't manage lifecycle
- Use for stateful beans

RequestHandler h1 = context.getBean(RequestHandler.class);
RequestHandler h2 = context.getBean(RequestHandler.class);
h1 == h2  // false
```

REQUEST (Web only):
```
One instance per HTTP request
- Lives for duration of request
- Automatically destroyed after response
- Different instance per request

@Bean
@Scope("request")
public RequestContext context() { }
```

SESSION (Web only):
```
One instance per user session
- Lives for entire user session
- Different instance per user
- Persisted in HttpSession

@Bean
@Scope("session")
public UserSession userSession() { }
```

SCOPE GOTCHA:
```java
// PROBLEM: Singleton with stateful field
@Component
public class UserService {
    private String currentUser;  // SHARED!
}

// SOLUTION: Make Request-scoped
@Component
@Scope("request")
public class UserContext {
    private String currentUser;  // Safe
}
```

BEST PRACTICES:
1. Default to SINGLETON (stateless)
2. Use REQUEST for user context
3. Use SESSION for user-scoped state
4. Use PROTOTYPE for stateful objects
5. Test scope carefully

Transient keyword controls which fields are serialized. Critical for security and efficiency.

WHAT IS TRANSIENT:
Marks fields that should NOT be serialized.

CODE:
```java
public class User implements Serializable {
    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

    private String name;  // Serialized
    private transient String password;  // NOT serialized
    private transient int tempCounter;  // NOT serialized
}

User user = new User("John", "secret123");

// Serialize
ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(fos);
oos.writeObject(user);
oos.close();

// Deserialize
ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(fis);
User deserialized = (User) ois.readObject();
ois.close();

// Result:
// deserialized.name = "John"
// deserialized.password = null  // Lost!
```

WHY USE TRANSIENT:

1. SECURITY:
```java
public class BankAccount implements Serializable {
    private String accountNumber;
    private transient String pin;  // Never serialize PIN
    private transient String cvv;  // Never serialize CVV
}
```

2. TEMPORARY DATA:
```java
public class Cache implements Serializable {
    private List<Data> persistedData;
    private transient Map<String, Object> tempCache;  // Runtime only
}
```

3. LARGE DATA:
```java
public class Document implements Serializable {
    private String content;
    private transient byte[] largeBuffer;  // Skip expensive data
}
```

DEFAULT VALUE AFTER DESERIALIZATION:
```
objects -> null
primitives -> 0 (numbers), false (boolean), chr(0) (char)
```

CUSTOM SERIALIZATION:
For sensitive handling:

```java
public class User implements Serializable {
    private String name;
    private transient String password;

    private void writeObject(ObjectOutputStream oos) 
        throws IOException {
        oos.defaultWriteObject();
        // Custom: encrypt password before writing
        oos.writeObject(encrypt(password));
    }

    private void readObject(ObjectInputStream ois) 
        throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {
        ois.defaultReadObject();
        // Custom: decrypt password after reading
        this.password = decrypt((String) ois.readObject());
    }
}
```

BEST PRACTICES:
1. Mark sensitive fields transient
2. Provide default values for deserialization
3. Always define serialVersionUID
4. Document serialization contract
5. Consider custom serialization for security

PRODUCTION: Never serialize passwords, tokens, or sensitive data. Always use transient.

Volatile ensures visibility of changes across threads. Critical for concurrent programming.

THE PROBLEM (Without volatile):
```
Thread 1:                Thread 2:
read flag = false        read flag = false
do work                  do work
set flag = true          ...
(maybe delayed)
                         still reads flag = false!
                         NO VISIBILITY
```

VOLATILE SOLUTION:
```java
public class SharedFlag {
    private volatile boolean flag = false;  // Visible across threads

    public void setFlag() {
        flag = true;  // Immediately visible to other threads
    }

    public boolean getFlag() {
        return flag;  // Always reads latest value
    }
}
```

VOLATILE GUARANTEES:

1. VISIBILITY:
- Changes visible to all threads immediately
- No CPU cache delays

2. ORDERING:
- Prevents reordering around volatile field
- Establishes happens-before relationship

3. ATOMICITY:
- Read/write operations atomic
- But NOT compound operations (check-then-act)

CORRECT USE:
```java
public class VolatileExample {
    private volatile boolean running = true;

    public void shutdown() {
        running = false;  // Thread-safe
    }

    public void process() {
        while (running) {  // Always sees latest
            doWork();
        }
    }
}
```

INCORRECT USE (Not thread-safe):
```java
public class Counter {
    private volatile int count = 0;

    public void increment() {
        count++;  // RACE CONDITION!
        // Read, increment, write are separate operations
        // Two threads can read same value, increment, lose one
    }
}
```

WHEN NOT TO USE VOLATILE:
- Compound operations (increment, check-then-act)
- Need mutual exclusion
- Multiple fields need consistency

ALTERNATIVES:
```java
// Use AtomicInteger for atomic operations
private AtomicInteger count = new AtomicInteger(0);
public void increment() {
    count.incrementAndGet();  // Atomic
}

// Use synchronized for mutual exclusion
private int count = 0;
public synchronized void increment() {
    count++;
}
```

VOLATILE vs SYNCHRONIZED:
```
Volatile:     Lightweight, visibility only
Synchronized: Heavier, visibility + mutual exclusion
```

PRODUCTION: Volatile is for flags and status. Use AtomicInteger for counters, synchronized for complex operations.

Understanding operation types is essential for writing efficient stream code.

INTERMEDIATE OPERATIONS:
Return Stream, can be chained, are LAZY.

COMMON INTERMEDIATE OPERATIONS:
```java
List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

// filter(Predicate) - Keep elements matching condition
numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)  // [2, 4]
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// map(Function) - Transform elements
numbers.stream()
    .map(n -> n * 2)  // [2, 4, 6, 8, 10]
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// flatMap(Function) - Flatten nested streams
List<List<Integer>> lists = Arrays.asList(
    Arrays.asList(1, 2),
    Arrays.asList(3, 4)
);
lists.stream()
    .flatMap(List::stream)  // [1, 2, 3, 4]
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// limit(long) - Take first n elements
numbers.stream()
    .limit(3)  // [1, 2, 3]
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// skip(long) - Skip first n elements
numbers.stream()
    .skip(2)  // [3, 4, 5]
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// distinct() - Remove duplicates
Arrays.asList(1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 3).stream()
    .distinct()  // [1, 2, 3]
    .forEach(System.out::println);

// sorted() - Sort elements
numbers.stream()
    .sorted()  // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    .forEach(System.out::println);
```

TERMINAL OPERATIONS:
Convert Stream to result, trigger execution, are EAGER.

COMMON TERMINAL OPERATIONS:
```java
// forEach(Consumer) - Side effect for each element
numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n > 2)
    .forEach(System.out::println);  // [3, 4, 5]

// collect(Collector) - Gather into collection
List<Integer> evens = numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());  // [2, 4]

// reduce(BinaryOperator) - Combine to single value
int sum = numbers.stream()
    .reduce(0, Integer::sum);  // 15

// count() - Count elements
long count = numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n > 2)
    .count();  // 3

// min(Comparator), max(Comparator) - Find extremes
int min = numbers.stream()
    .min(Integer::compareTo)
    .orElse(Integer.MAX_VALUE);  // 1

// findFirst() - Get first element
int first = numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> n > 2)
    .findFirst()
    .orElse(-1);  // 3

// anyMatch(Predicate) - Check if any match
boolean hasEven = numbers.stream()
    .anyMatch(n -> n % 2 == 0);  // true

// allMatch(Predicate) - Check if all match
boolean allPositive = numbers.stream()
    .allMatch(n -> n > 0);  // true
```

LAZY EVALUATION:
```java
List<Integer> result = numbers.stream()
    .filter(n -> { System.out.println("filter " + n); return n > 2; })
    .map(n -> { System.out.println("map " + n); return n * 2; })
    .limit(2)
    .collect(Collectors.toList());  // Terminal: triggers execution

// Output:
// filter 1, filter 2, filter 3, map 3, filter 4, map 4, limit reached
// NOT: filter all 5, then map, then limit
```

PRODUCTION TIP: Chains with multiple intermediate operations are lazy until terminal operation.

Immutable objects are thread-safe by design. Essential for concurrent applications.

WHAT IS IMMUTABLE:
Object cannot be modified after creation.

HOW TO CREATE IMMUTABLE CLASS:

```java
public final class ImmutableUser {
    private final String name;
    private final int age;
    private final List<String> addresses;  // Collection!

    public ImmutableUser(String name, int age, List<String> addresses) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        // DEFENSIVE COPY for collections
        this.addresses = new ArrayList<>(addresses);
    }

    public String getName() { return name; }
    public int getAge() { return age; }
    public List<String> getAddresses() {
        // Return unmodifiable copy
        return Collections.unmodifiableList(new ArrayList<>(addresses));
    }

    // NO SETTERS
}
```

KEY RULES:
1. Class declared final (prevent extension)
2. All fields private and final
3. Initialize in constructor
4. No setters
5. Return copies of mutable objects

EXAMPLE: String is immutable
```java
String s = "Hello";
String s2 = s.toUpperCase();  // Creates new String
// s still "Hello", s2 is "HELLO"
```

WHY IMMUTABILITY MATTERS:

1. THREAD-SAFETY:
```java
// Immutable: no synchronization needed
ImmutableUser user = new ImmutableUser("John", 30);
user.getName();  // Safe from multiple threads

// Mutable: needs synchronization
MutableUser user = new MutableUser("John");
synchronized (user) {
    user.setName("Jane");  // Need locks
}
```

2. CACHE-FRIENDLY:
```java
Map<ImmutableUser, String> userCache = new HashMap<>();
// Safe to use as key (no changes)
userCache.put(user, "admin");
```

3. SECURITY:
```java
// Can safely share without fear of modification
public ImmutableUser getUser() {
    return user;  // Caller can't modify
}
```

JAVA IMMUTABLE CLASSES:
- String
- Integer, Long, Double, etc.
- LocalDate, LocalDateTime
- Pattern

MODERN APPROACH (Records in Java 14+):
```java
public record User(
    String name,
    int age,
    List<String> addresses
) {}
// Automatically immutable!
User user = new User("John", 30, List.of("NYC"));
```

PRODUCTION BENEFITS:
- No synchronization overhead
- Easier to reason about
- Safe to share across threads
- Works well as map keys
- Enables compiler optimizations

PRODUCTION TIP: Prefer immutability. It eliminates entire classes of bugs.
